He is the god of water and is said to control {{ill|Dragon|ja|竜}}. Originally, he was the {{ill|Asura|ja|アスラ}} of the ancient Indo-Iranian people, known as {{ill|Varuna|ja|ヴァルナ (神)|lt=Varuna|lt_ja=ヴァルナ}}.

In the Vedas, Varuna held an important position and was endowed with the attributes of a sky god, a god of justice (that is, the deity of contracts and righteousness), and a water god. In the western regions, Varuna became {{ill|Ahura Mazda|ja|アフラ・マズダー}} and the supreme god of {{ill|Zoroastrianism|ja|ゾロアスター教}}.

However, in the eastern regions, his status as the primordial god was usurped by {{ill|Brahma|ja|ブラフマー}}, and later his role as the god of justice was taken over by the god of the dead, {{ill|Yama|ja|閻魔|lt=Yama|lt_ja=ヤマ}}, leaving him with only his attribute as a water god. When incorporated into Buddhism, he became known as “Suiten,” one of the Twelve Devas guarding the west.

== Mantra ==
oṃ varuṇāya svāhā

オン バロダヤ ソワカ<ref>{{ill|Gotō Asuka|ja|悟東あすか}} "What the Gods and Buddhas Secretly Taught Me", 2018, Diamond Inc., p.202</ref>

== Suiten in Japan ==
In Japan, during the period of {{ill|Shinbutsu Shūgō|ja|神仏習合}}, by the association with the character for “water,” Suiten became syncretized with {{ill|Mizubunshin|ja|水分神|lt=Heavenly and National Water Deity|lt_ja=天之水分神・国之水分神}} (あめのみくまりのかみ・くにのみくまりのかみ). Although Mizubunshin originally had no relation to children, the pronunciation “mikumari” came to be associated with “mikomori” (childcare), and thus Suiten came to be revered as a deity of safe childbirth, child-rearing, and as a protector of children.

{{Citation needed|date=December 2019|During the {{ill|Separation of Shinto and Buddhism|ja|神仏分離}}, since the original divine status of Varuna was that of the supreme and primordial god, it was interpreted as equivalent to the primordial god {{ill|Ame-no-Minakanushi|ja|天御中主神}} in the {{ill|Japanese Mythology|ja|日本神話|lt=Kojiki-Kuniyoshi Myths|lt_ja=記紀神話}}, and the enshrined deity of {{ill|Suiten Shrine|ja|水天宮}} was changed to Ame-no-Minakanushi. Furthermore, since {{ill|Emperor Andoku|ja|安徳天皇}} entered the water while still reigning, he was called the Water Emperor and came to be identified with Suiten.}}

By extension from the dragon, in some regions and temples the {{ill|Snake|ja|蛇}} is regarded as its symbolic animal.

As a {{ill|National Treasure|ja|国宝}}, a {{ill|Buddhist Painting|ja|仏画}} (painted on silk, 144.3 x 126.5 cm) depicting the water deity is housed at the {{ill|Kyoto National Museum|ja|京都国立博物館}}. This work has been used in the annual New Year’s ritual at the Imperial Court’s Shingon-in since the {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代}}, and it is one of the images of the {{ill|Twelve Devas|ja|十二天}} produced in 1127 (the 2nd year of {{ill|Daiji (Japan)|ja|大治 (日本)|lt=Daiji|lt_ja=大治}}).<ref>{{Cite web|title=Water Deity Statue (Suiten-zō) (Among the Twelve Devas)|url=https://www.kyohaku.go.jp/jp/syuzou/meihin/butsuga/item05_07.html|accessdate=2019-02-08|publisher=Kyoto National Museum|language=ja}}</ref>

[[File:Suiten Statue (Hayato).jpg|thumb|Water Deity Statue. Hayato-zuka Museum collection]]

