'''Suiten''' (水天) is one of the {{ill|Buddhism|ja|仏教|qq=draft|qq=draft}}’s {{ill|Celestial Beings|ja|天部|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, who is said to live to the west of {{ill|Mount Sumeru|ja|須弥山|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. He is one of the {{ill|Twelve Devas|ja|十二天|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

== Divine Status ==
He is the god of water and is said to control {{ill|Dragon|ja|竜|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Originally, he was the {{ill|Asura|ja|アスラ|qq=draft|qq=draft}} of the ancient Indo-Iranian people, known as {{ill|Varuna|ja|ヴァルナ (神)|lt=Varuna|lt_ja=ヴァルナ|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

In the Vedas, Varuna held an important position and was endowed with the attributes of a sky god, a god of justice (that is, the deity of contracts and righteousness), and a water god. In the western regions, Varuna became {{ill|Ahura Mazda|ja|アフラ・マズダー|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and the supreme god of {{ill|Zoroastrianism|ja|ゾロアスター教|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

However, in the eastern regions, his status as the primordial god was usurped by {{ill|Brahma|ja|ブラフマー|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and later his role as the god of justice was taken over by the god of the dead, {{ill|Yama|ja|閻魔|lt=Yama|lt_ja=ヤマ|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, leaving him with only his attribute as a water god. When incorporated into Buddhism, he became known as “Suiten,” one of the Twelve Devas guarding the west.

== Mantra ==
oṃ varuṇāya svāhā

オン バロダヤ ソワカ<ref>{{ill|Gotō Asuka|ja|悟東あすか|qq=draft|qq=draft}} "What the Gods and Buddhas Secretly Taught Me", 2018, Diamond Inc., p.202</ref>

