By extension from the dragon, in some regions and temples the {{ill|Snake|ja|蛇|qq=draft|qq=draft}} is regarded as its symbolic animal.

As a {{ill|National Treasure|ja|国宝|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a {{ill|Buddhist Painting|ja|仏画|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (painted on silk, 144.3 x 126.5 cm) depicting the water deity is housed at the {{ill|Kyoto National Museum|ja|京都国立博物館|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. This work has been used in the annual New Year’s ritual at the Imperial Court’s Shingon-in since the {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and it is one of the images of the {{ill|Twelve Devas|ja|十二天|qq=draft|qq=draft}} produced in 1127 (the 2nd year of {{ill|Daiji (Japan)|ja|大治 (日本)|lt=Daiji|lt_ja=大治|qq=draft|qq=draft}}).<ref>{{Cite web|title=Water Deity Statue (Suiten-zō) (Among the Twelve Devas)|url=https://www.kyohaku.go.jp/jp/syuzou/meihin/butsuga/item05_07.html|accessdate=2019-02-08|publisher=Kyoto National Museum|language=ja}}</ref>

